This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

As the C# docs mention - value types have always an default value:

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/builtin-types/integral-numeric-types

> The default value of each integral type is zero, 0.

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/builtin-types/default-values

> Any built-in integral numeric type | 0 (zero)
> Any built-in floating-point numeric type | 0 (zero)
> bool | false
> char | '\0' (U+0000)

So although these types have a default value and are therefore always initialized, there is the compiler error "CS0165 Use of unassigned local variable" if I create a local integer variable without explicitly assigning a value. Instead of that, I can create a field in a class without that compiler error.

**Version Used**: 
- Microsoft (R) Visual C# Compiler Version 4.6.0-3.23259.8 (c3cc1d0c)
- Microsoft Visual Studio Enterprise 2022 Version 17.6.5

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Create a local variable of type int, bool, double, ... and use it without initializing it with its default value.
```csharp
int i;
int j;

// Error CS0165 Use of unassigned local variable 'i'
j = i;
```


**Expected Behavior**:

```csharp
int i;
int j;

// no error
j = i;
```

**Actual Behavior**:

```csharp
int i;
int j;

// Error CS0165 Use of unassigned local variable 'i'
j = i;
```

But an uninitialized field is valid:

```csharp
internal class IntProperty
{
	// no error
	int myVar;

	public int MyProperty
	{
		get { return myVar; }
		set { myVar = value; }
	}
}
```

Either a value type has a default value, as documented everywhere, then it does not have to be initialized explicitly (see "CA1805: Do not initialize unnecessarily"). A different treatment between a local variable or a field variable of a class is not understandable.

If a value type has no default value, then it must be initialized everywhere and the documentation must be adapted accordingly.

**Version Used**: Version 17.8.0 Preview 1.0 [33911.468.main]

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```c#
class C
{
    // This class has a comment here.

    private readonly string _field;

    public C(string field)
    {
        _field = field;
    }
}
```

Invoke "Use primary constructor (and remove fields)".

```c#
class C(string field)
{
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

The comment is not stripped from the class.

```c#
class C(string field)
{
    // This class has a comment here.
}
```

